<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-684-450  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 684 450.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  July 30 1990 v7 n30 p120(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Small businesses plan to increase PC purchases. (Business ResearchGroup market survey)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fisher, Susan E.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Business Research Group (surveys).andO;Topic:     Small businessBusiness PlanningEquipment AcquisitionMicrocomputersMarket SurveyForecasting.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Year-ahead computer purchase plans in the small-business sector.andO;(graph)Through what channel will they buy them? (graph)PC Week stock index. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Sales of personal computers to small U.S.andP;  businesses will reach $2 billionin 1991, according to a recent survey of 700 small businesses.andM;The survey, done by Business Research Group, a market-research firm inNewton, Mass., showed that small businesses -- those with less than 100employees -- are attractive as customers for both PC vendors and networkingcompanies.andM;The survey indicated that only 27 percent of small businesses with PCs arecurrently using LANs, although they have plans to increase their PCpurchases.andM;The majority of personal computers -- 55 percent -- that will be acquired bysmall businesses in the next 12 months will be XT/AT-class machines,according to the survey.andM;Thirty-nine percent of the respondents said they intend to buy a 386-basedPC.andP;  Fifteen percent of the small businesses surveyed are considering buyingthe Macintosh, and 9 percent are looking at IBM PS/2 computers.andM;-- Susan E. Fisher</TEXT></DOC>